title: For Sale:  Steyr S9A1 9mm
postcontent: Steyr S9A1 9mm, two mags THE STEYR PISTOL LINE IS ONE OF MY PERSONAL FAVORITES.  IF YOU LIKE THE OTHER PISTOL MADE IN AUSTRIA, YOU'LL LOVE THIS PISTOL.  THE TRAPEZOID SITES ARE KIND OF FUNKY AT FIRST, BUT DOESN'T TAKE ANY TIME GETTING USED TO.  The Steyr S9A1 striker-fired pistol is a sub-compact, semi-automatic, double-action handgun available as the S9A1 chambered in 9x19mm Parabellum or the S40-A1 chambered in .40 Smith & Wesson. The smallest of Steyr’s pistol line, the S9A1 has a 3.6” (91mm) barrel and the same short overall length as the C-A1 but features a short grip for ultra-concealment. As with each model in the Steyr A1 line of products, the pistol features a low bore-axis which minimizes recoil and improves control while the ergonomic grip offers optimal control for a variety of hand sizes. The lower frame of the gun offers a standard slide-lock thumb tab, right-handed magazine ejection button and pivoting break-down lever. A key-operated manual safety feature is located next to the break-down lever and 2 keys are provided with each pistol. An integrated Picatinny rail allows for simple mounting of a laser or light and slide-racking grooves on the back of the slide allow for a firm grip when manually operating the action.  S9-A1    Caliber 9mm   Magazine 10+1   Trigger Reset Action (double action)   Grip Frame Synthetic Grip   Dimensions 6.5"x4.8"x1.2"   Barrel Length 3.6"   Weight 1.67 lbs    Great pistol Review by SRW       Quality      As good or better than any striker fired polymer handgun I have fired. Not what I would call a sub-compact, comparable to mid sized Glocks. Ergonomics are excellent. I have fairly large hands while my wife's hands are very small yet I fits well for each. Very easy to control recoil. Approximately 1000 rounds fired and I only recall one malfunction that could be blamed on the gun, a failure to extract. All rounds fired have been reloads so it could have been my ammo. 115 and 124 grain ball and a few JHP bullets, it isn't picky. The Trapezoid sights take some practice if your used to three dots. I like them, fast and precise. Still debating on getting aftermarket tritium three dot. The trigger is excellent for a striker fired gun. I like the Ghost triggers in my Glocks, the Steyr is as good or better out of the box. Reset is short but not as easy to feel as the Glock, takes a few hundred rounds to get the hang of it.  I also have the M40-A1, it is equally good. If you are looking for a striker fired gun take a look at the Steyrs, pull the trigger, check out the sights and grip, it may be just what you want. While no handgun is perfect for everyone, these are top quality guns in every way. (Posted on 3/11/2016)Great look and feel Review by JanSorry, not interested in trades.  All FFL rules and regs apply.  Buyer pays shipping or sales tax.Buy this pistol online at www.copsgunshop.net.
